What is the measure of an angle, in degrees, if its supplement is six times its complement?
inference:
Let the angle be x.
The supplement of the angle is 180 - x.
The complement of the angle is 90 - x.
We are given that the supplement is six times the complement.
So, 180 - x = 6(90 - x)
180 - x = 540 - 6x
180 - 540 = -6x + x
-360 = -5x
x = 72
Final Answer: $\boxed{72}$ degrees. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: Call the angle measure $x$. We are given that $180^{\circ}-x=6(90^{\circ}-x)$. This expands to $180^{\circ}-x=540^{\circ}-6x$ or $5x=360^{\circ}$ and $x=\boxed{72^{\circ}}$.
